Es it is written, For thy sake are wee
killed al the day long, and are counted
as sheepe for theslaughter. Neverthe
lesse, in all these thinges we overcome
through him that loved us. For I am
sure that neither death, nor life, nor an
gels, nor rule, nor poler, nor thinges
presetanor things to come, nor height,
nor depth, nor anie other creature
shal be able to separate us fro the love
of GOD which is in Christ lesu our
Lorde. Hitherto have I recited the
words of Paul.
The love of God woorketh in us a
will to erame our selves wholly to the
will and ordinaunces of him whom
we doe heartily love. Pea, it is plea
faunt and sweete to him that loveth
God, to doe the thing that he percei
veth is acceptable to God it it be done.
He that loveth, doeth in minde reve
rence him whom hee loveth. His eye
is never off him whom hee loveth. Hee
doth alwayes and in all thinges wish
for his dearling whom he loveth. His
onely joy is as oft as may bee to talke
with God, and agayne to heare the
wordes of God speaking in the Scrip
ture. For the Lorde in the Gospell
saithr If any man love me he wil keepe
my worde, he that loveth me not, doth

yee in my love, if yee keepe my com

Pea, it is plea faunt and sweete to him that loveth God, to doe the thing that he percei veth is acceptable to God it it be done. He that loveth, doeth in minde reve rence him whom hee loveth. His eye is never off him whom hee loveth. Hee doth alwayes and in all thinges wish for his dearling whom he loveth. His onely joy is as oft as may bee to talke with God, and agayne to heare the wordes of God speaking in the Scrip ture. For the Lorde in the Gospell saithr If any man love me he wil keepe my worde, he that loveth me not, doth not keepe my wordes. Agayne, Abide yee in my love, if yee keepe my com maundementes, yee shalk abide in my love, even as l also have kept my Fa thers commaundements and do abide in his love. And agayne, If any man love me, he will keepe my worde, and
my father will love him, and wee will
come to him and make our dwelling
in him
But nowe let us heare Moses the
seruaunt of God declaring and tea
ching us the way and manner how to
love GOD, to wit, howe great love
ought to bee in the elect. Thou shalt
saith he, love the Lord thy God, with
all thy heart, with all thy soule, and.
with all thy skrength. The very same
words in a manner did our Lord in the
Gospell repeate, and saide: Thou shalt
love the Lorde thy God with all thy
heart, with all thy soule, with all thy
strength, and with all thy minde. By
this we understande that the greatest,
love that may bee, is required at our
handes to God warde : as that which
challengeth man wholly how bigge so
ever he be and all the parts of man as,
peculiar unto it selfe. In the monde is,
mans understanding. In the heart
is the seate of his affections and will.,
The strength of man contayneth all,
mans abilitie, as his verie woordes,
deedes, counsell, riches, and his whole
substance. Finally, the soule is the life
of man. And we verily are commaun
ded to employ all these uppon the love
of God, when wee are bidden to love
God with all our soule, with all our
strength, with our whole minde, and
our whole heart. Nothing is over
sipt, but all is cont ayned in this. We
are Gods wholly & altogether, let us
altogether therefore and wholly love
God. Let nothing in all the world bee
dearer to us than God, let us not spare
for Gods sake anie thing of all that
which we possesse howe deare to us or
good soever itbee, but let us forsake,
spende, and give it for Gods sake, and
as the Lord by his worde appointeth,
For in doing so we love God before
